Incident Response Simulation and Infrastructure as Code Implementation
1. Title
Design and Deployment of a Containerized Microservices System with Terraform-Based
Infrastructure Provisioning and Incident Response Simulation
2. Objectives
The primary objective of this project is to integrate Infrastructure as Code (IaC) principles with
Site Reliability Engineering (SRE) practices by designing, deploying, and analyzing a
containerized microservices-based application.
The project aims to:
1. Implement a microservices architecture using containerization technologies.
2. Provision infrastructure using Terraform to ensure reproducibility and automation.
3. Deploy and orchestrate services using Docker Compose.
4. Integrate monitoring and observability tools.
5. Simulate a realistic production-level incident.
6. Conduct a structured incident response process.
7. Produce a comprehensive postmortem analysis.
3. System Requirements
3.1 Functional Requirements
The system shall:
1. Provide a web-based interface for user interaction.
2. Support user authentication and authorization.
3. Enable retrieval and display of product data.
4. Allow users to perform transactional operations (e.g., order creation).
5. Ensure communication between independent backend services.
6. Collect and expose system metrics for monitoring.
7. Detect and log service failures.
3.2 Non-Functional Requirements
The system shall:
1. Ensure scalability through modular microservices.
2. Maintain fault isolation between services.
3. Provide observability via metrics and dashboards.
4. Enable automated deployment using IaC.
5. Support containerized execution across environments.
6. Ensure reproducibility of infrastructure and services.
4. Technology Stack
The system shall be implemented using the following technologies:
● Backend: Python (FastAPI) or any other Programming language(that supports
microservices)
● Frontend: JavaScript served via Nginx
● Database: PostgreSQL
● Containerization: Docker
● Orchestration: Docker Compose and Stack
● Monitoring: Prometheus and Grafana
● Infrastructure as Code: Terraform
5. System Architecture
The application follows a microservices-based architecture, consisting of independent services
communicating over HTTP.
Core Components
● Frontend Layer: User interface served via Nginx
● API Gateway / Reverse Proxy: Request routing
● Microservices:
a. Authentication Service
b. Product Service
c. Order Service
d. User Service
e. Chat between User Service
● Database Layer: PostgreSQL
● Monitoring Layer:
a. Prometheus (metrics collection)
b. Grafana (visualization)
6. Infrastructure as Code (Assignment 5)
6.1 Objective
To provision the required infrastructure using Terraform in a declarative and reproducible
manner.
6.2 Requirements
The Terraform configuration shall:
1. Provision a virtual machine (VM) or cloud instance.
2. Configure network access rules, including:
a. HTTP (80)
b. Grafana (3000)
c. Prometheus (9090)
d. SSH (22)
3. Output the public IP address of the instance.
4. Ensure infrastructure reproducibility using:
a. terraform init
b. terraform plan
c. terraform apply
6.3 Expected Deliverables
1. main.tf
2. variables.tf
3. outputs.tf
4. terraform.tfvars
5. Deployment documentation
7. Containerized Deployment
The system shall be deployed using Docker Compose, including:
1. Frontend container
2. Backend microservices containers
3. PostgreSQL database container
4. Prometheus container
5. Grafana container
Each service shall:
1. Run in an isolated container
2. Communicate via internal Docker networking
3. Use environment variables for configuration
8. Monitoring and Observability
The system shall integrate monitoring tools:
1. Prometheus shall collect metrics from services.
2. Grafana shall visualize system performance.
3. System health shall be validated via:
a. Service availability
b. Metrics endpoints
c. Dashboard visualization
9. Incident Response Simulation (Assignment 4)
9.1 Objective
To simulate a realistic system failure and evaluate the response process.
9.2 Incident Scenario
A failure shall be introduced in the Order Service, caused by incorrect database configuration
(e.g., invalid connection string or hostname).
9.3 Requirements
The simulation shall include:
1. Incident Detection
a. Identification through monitoring tools (Grafana/Prometheus)
b. Observation of system errors or service downtime
2. Incident Analysis
a. Examination of logs and container status
b. Identification of root cause
3. Incident Mitigation
a. Correction of configuration errors
b. Restart of affected services
4. Service Restoration
a. Verification of system functionality
b. Confirmation via metrics and user interface
9.4 Incident Report Requirements
The incident report shall include:
1. Incident summary
2. Impact assessment
3. Severity classification
4. Timeline of events
5. Root cause analysis
6. Mitigation steps
7. Resolution confirmation
10. Postmortem Analysis
10.1 Objective
To evaluate the incident and propose improvements to prevent recurrence.
10.2 Requirements
The postmortem document shall include:
1. Incident Overview
2. Customer Impact
3. Root Cause Analysis
4. Detection and Response Evaluation
5. Resolution Summary
6. Lessons Learned
7. Action Items
10.3 Action Items
Action items shall:
1. Address system weaknesses
2. Improve monitoring and alerting
3. Enhance deployment reliability
4. Reduce future incident risk
